SIMPLE: miscreant
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Miscreant
<hw>Mis"cre*ant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF.
<ets>mescreant</ets>, F. <ets>m⟦eacute⟧cr⟦eacute⟧ant</ets>; pref.
<ets>mes-</ets> (L. <ets>minus</ets> less) + p. pr. fr. L.
<ets>credere</ets> to believe. See <er>Creed</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>One who holds a false religious faith; a
misbeliever.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Spenser. De
Quincey.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou oughtest not to be slothful to the destruction of the
<qex>miscreants</qex>, but to constrain them to obey our Lord God.</q>
<rj><qau>Rivers.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One not restrained by Christian principles; an
unscrupulous villain; a depraved person; a vile wretch.</def>
<rj><au>Addison.</au></rj></p>

<p><ent>Miscreant</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Miscreant
<hw>Mis"cre*ant</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Holding a false
religious faith.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Destitute of conscience; unscrupulous; villainous;
base; depraved.</def> <rj><au>Pope.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscreate</ent>⟦br⟧
